<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   N-S Religious Group Agrees on Joint Event </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1003105994 Seoul YONHAP in English 1023 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1003105994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 10 (YONHAP) -- South and North Korean 
Chondo-kyo [religious organization] delegates met in Beijing on 
Thursday morning and agreed that 15 North Korean Chondo-kyo 
delegates would attend ceremonies taking place in Seoul on March 
21 to mark the centenary of the Tonghak peasants uprising. 
  An official at the Seoul's Chondo-kyo headquarters said that 
at the Beijing meeting, the two sides decided to adopt a joint 
statement at the Seoul ceremonies and to discuss procedural 
matters at Panmunjom on North Koreans' coming to Seoul. 
  He said, however, that it is not certain if North Koreans 
could attend the Seoul ceremonies because the Seoul government 
plans to allow the two sides' Panmunjom contacts to discuss 
procedural matters only when the exchange of special envoys is 
realized. 
  The Beijing contact was attended by Pang Chin-kyo, 
Chondo-kyo 
chairman, and Hong Chang-hwa, an official of Chondo-kyo College, 
from Seoul, and Yu Yong-mi, chairman of the North Korean 
Chondo-kyo Central Committee. 
  Materialization of North Korean delegates' visit to Seoul 
would depend on the outcome of the South-North contact slated 
for coming Saturday [12 March] at Panmunjom on the issue of 
exchanging special envoys, the official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

