<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reshuffle of DPRK Economic Ministers Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1003022494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0112 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1003022494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 10 (YONHAP) -- North Korea recently 
reshuffled a number of economy-related ministers, suggesting a 
drastic change in its economic policy, NAEWOE press, the 
official North Korea watcher here, said on Wednesday. 
  Change may be forthcoming given that Pyongyang appointed 
Hong 
Sok-hyong and Kong Chin-tae as State Planning Commission 
chairman and vice premier, respectively, about two months ago, 
according to NAEWOE. 
  Four ministers were also replaced recently -- the forestry 
minister, Academy of Sciences president, mining industry 
minister and chairman of the State Commission of Science and 
Technology -- by unknown figures, NAEWOE said. 
  North Korea established a new Commission on Protection of 
the 
Environment last February, but its Chairman Yi Kon-il was 
replaced by Hwang Sang-chun recently. 
  The exact reason for the ministerial changes is not known, 
NAEWOE said. 

</TEXT>

