<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Adopts Minimum Wage System for Some Firms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1003075594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0746 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1003075594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 10 (YONHAP) -- North Korea has 
introduced a minimum wage system for foreign-invested 
enterprises to prepare for possible foreign investment in the 
future. 
  The system, however, appears to offer little incentive for 
foreign companies seeking to invest in North Korea on the 
strength of its cheap labor, as the minimum wage set for 
foreign-invested firms is much higher than the country's general 
wage level. 
  Late last year, North Korea's Administrative Council 
established a labor regulation laying down standard labor 
practices for foreign-invested firms, according to the Korea 
Trade Promotion Corp. (KOTRA). 
  The regulation, consisting of 48 articles in eight chapters, 
provides a minimum wage level and procedures for employing, 
dismissing and punishing employees and for settling labor 
disputes at foreign-invested firms. 
  In Article 26, the regulation stipulates that the minimum 
monthly wage paid by foreign-invested firms shall not be less 
than 220 won (about 100 U.S. dollars). 
  This minimum wage level for foreign-invested firms compares 
with monthly pay of 30 to 50 dollars for ordinary North Korean 
workers and the 73-dollar minimum monthly wage for workers in 
the free trade zone. 
  KOTRA officials say the higher minimum wage for 
foreign-invested firms will hinder the Stalinist country's 
efforts to attract foreign investment. 
  The regulation also provides that joint-venture firms with 
foreign equity investment shall give priority either to workers 
of North Korean partner companies or to those recommended by the 
relevant employment office when they hire workers -- another 
stumbling block to active foreign investment -- according to the 
officials. 
  Foreign firms operating in North Korea have previously set 
working conditions for their employees through negotiations with 
their North Korean partners or North Korean government 
authorities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

