<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Insurance Firm Allowed To Establish Agents </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1003020494 Seoul THE KOREA HERALD in English 10 Mar 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> SK1003020494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul THE KOREA HERALD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Government has permitted Alexander &amp; 
Alexander, 
a U.S. insurance company, and Willis Faber &amp; Dumas, a British 
insurance company, to establish agents in Korea, the Ministry of 
Finance said yesterday. 
  The permission was granted on condition that they close 
their 
existing representative offices in the nation, the ministry said. 
  When the insurance companies obtain approval from the 
government after completing the procedure of investment by 
foreigners, they will be able to establish agents who are 
allowed to sell policies issued by domestic insurance companies. 
  The agents are required to conclude contracts with domestic 
insurance companies to sell policies on their behalf. But the 
agents are not allowed to sell policies issued by foreign 
insurance companies, the ministry said. 

</TEXT>

