<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK To Scale Back Concessions on GATT List Items </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1003025394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0209 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1003025394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 10 (YONHAP) -- South Korea has decided 
to scale back tariff concessions on nine industrial items in its 
list of Uruguay Round commitments due to be submitted to the 
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) on Friday. 
  The Economic Planning Board presided over an international 
policy meeting Thursday and decided to impose duties of 3 
percent to 4 percent on the nine industrial imports rather than 
abolishing them, as agreed earlier with the United States in the 
GATT-sponsored negotiations last December. 
  In its country schedule, Washington also scaled back tariff 
concessions recently on the grounds that Japan and the European 
union had failed to make comparable offers. 
  Subject to 3-percent duties are three copper products -- 
tube 
or pipe fittings of copper and alloy, stranded wire copper 
cable, plated bands and the like. 
  Under 4-percent tariffs came computer equipment -- input and 
output units, printers, monitors and cathode-ray tube terminals 
-- and semiconductor devices -- piezoelectric crystals and 
crystal vibrators. 
  With the changes, Korea presented non-tariffication offers 
on 
965 manufactured items instead of the initial 974. 
  The United States had proposed abolishing tariffs on some 
electronic, non-ferrous and wood products last December but, 
rebuffed by Japan, it submitted smaller tariff concessions in 
the industrial section at the GATT on Feb. 28, a Finance 
Ministry official said. 
  Seoul, accordingly, decided to offer tariff cuts instead of 
none on the same nine items that Washington had scaled down, he 
said. 
  It again followed Washington in setting rates, levying the 
same 3 percent tariffs on copper goods as the United States and 
other major countries and slashing the current 8-percent duties 
on electronic goods 50 percent to 4 percent, as was done by the 
Americans. 
  Together with its agricultural country schedule, Korea will 
submit the revised list of industrial offers to the Geneva-based 
GATT headquarters on Friday. 
  The schedules of every country undergo screening until March 
21, and those drawing complaints from concerned exporting or 
importing countries will have to go through extra consultations. 
  Seoul officials say they will actively participate in the 
screening process to protect their country's interests. 
  Once the screening is finished, the overall Uruguay Round 
accord -- whether it is revised from the Dec. 15 version or not 
-- will be signed at a ministerial meeting in Morocco in April. 

</TEXT>

