<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   YONHAP Reports on Yi Pok-hon </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1003113494 Seoul YONHAP in English 1119 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1003113494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 10 (YONHAP) -- A South Korean man who 
had allegedly been working for North Korea abroad was arrested 
by the Agency for National Security Planning (NSP) on Thursday. 
  The spy suspect was identified only as Yi Pok-hon, age 32. 
  An NSP official said on Thursday Yi fled the country in 
April 
1990 soon after he was placed on a wanted list on swindle 
charges. 
  Later in September 1991 he joined the "Asia Sharon," a 
criminal organization, based in Dacca, Bangladesh, and worked 
for North Korea while at the criminal ring, the official said. 
  Yi is suspected of having entered North Korea six times from 
April 1992 through November 1993 to receive espionage training 
and instructions. 
  The official said he was first picked up by North Korea in 
April 1992 when he called at the Pyongyang Embassy in Bangkok to 
solicit its help in giving shooting training to "Asia Sharon" 
gangsters. 
  The instructions he received from North Korea were to 
assassinate anti-Pyongyang Koreans abroad and win over bosses of 
organized criminal rings in South Korea. 
  The NSP official said Yi gave 1.5 million dollars to North 
Korea for giving military training to "Asia Sharon" members and 
also supplied some espionage items such as forged passports, 
visa cards and traveler's checks to Pyongyang. 
  He is further alleged to have arranged a contract for the 
sale of 500 million dollars' worth of North Korean weapons to a 
guerrila organization in a Southeast Asian country. 
  Yi was arrested by public security authorities of China on 
last March 8, deported to Korea and was carried away by the NSP 
on arrival at Kimpo Airport. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

