<F P=100> INTER-ASIAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Brunei Agrees to ASEAN Invitation for Burma </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0903023894 Bangkok BANGKOK POST in English 9 Mar 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> BK0903023894 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok BANGKOK POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brunei has confirmed that it is in favour of 
inviting Burma to an annual meeting of foreign ministers of the 
Association of Southeast Asian Nations in Bangkok in July, 
Foreign Minister Prasong Sunsiri said yesterday. 
  Brunei believes the time is "appropriate" to invite Burma, 
Squadron Leader Prasong quoted Brunei Foreign Permanent 
Secretary Lim Jok Seng as saying. 
  Dato Lim conveyed the message from his foreign minister, 
Prince Mohamed Bolkiah, to Sqn Ldr [Squadron Leader] Prasong 
during a, 30-minute meeting at the Foreign Ministry yesterday 
Dato Lim is in Bangkok to attend a meeting of ASEAN senior 
officials, who on Monday agreed in principle to invite Burma to 
their foreign ministers' annual conference. 
  With Brunei's endorsement, Thailand's attempt to bring Burma 
out of isolation has won the support of all ASEAN partners, 
officials noted. 
  But Sqn Ldr Prasong acknowledged that ASEAN member states 
remain undecided as to whether to invite Rangoon as guest of the 
grouping, or to let Thailand issue the invitation as host 
country. 
  A Foreign Ministry official pointed out that Burma should be 
invited as Thailand's guest with the endorsement of other ASEAN 
members. 
  The Foreign Minister reiterated that the invitation would 
strengthen security in the region and encourage Burma to bring 
about political and economic reforms. 
  Meanwhile, a senior member of the military junta in Rangoon 
has met opposition leader Aung San Suu Kyi Voice of America 
reported yesterday. 
  THE NEW YORK TIMES quoted Intelligence chief Lt-Gen Khin 
Nyunt of the State Law and Order Restoration Council as saying 
that the meeting "produced nothing useful," VOA said in a report 
monitored. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-5781 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas047__a94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-047-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 March 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kumagai Urges Settlement of Problems With U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0403003894 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 2 Mar 94 
Evening Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0403003894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Minister of International Trade and Industry Hiroshi 
Kumagai attended a meeting at a Tokyo hotel on the morning of 2 
March to exchange views with leading manufacturers of industrial 
machinery. Kozaburo Nishimura, chairman of the Japan Society of 
Industrial Machinery Manufacturers, said: "Since intensifying 
Japan-U.S. friction has resulted in the yen's appreciation, we 
are now faced with a difficult situation. Therefore, I hope 
efforts will be made to prevent Japan-U.S. relations from being 
impaired." Many participants called for steady implementation of 
the economic stimulus package. Concerning Japan-U.S. ties, 
Minister Kumagai stressed: "Japan should resolutely carry out 
whatever is achievable and settle economic problems existing 
between our two countries as soon as possible." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

