<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MITI Official Views Chip Trade Talks Plans </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1003091794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0859 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1003091794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 10 KYODO -- Japan and the United 
States will hold two days of regular talks on semiconductor 
trade in Hawaii in mid-March, a Japanese trade official said 
Thursday [10 March]. The March 22-23 talks will follow a 
meeting from March 16 that will focus on calculating the foreign 
share in the Japanese semiconductor market for the 
October-December quarter last year, said an official at the 
Ministry of International Trade and Industry. 
  Under a 1991 trade pact, Japan and the United States agreed 
to a 20 percent goal for foreign market share by the end of 
1992. In the final quarter of 1992, the foreign market share 
exceeded the goal, reaching 20.2 percent under a U.S. formula. 
  According to the U.S. formula, the foreign share since has 
been in a downward trend, standing at 18.1 percent for the 
July-September quarter last year. Under a separate Japanese 
accounting method, which includes chips manufactured in Japan by 
foreign companies for their own use, the foreign share had risen 
above the 20 percent level for three successive quarters from 
the final quarter of 1992, but fell to 19.7 percent in the 
July-September quarter last year. 
  U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor has said he is 
concerned about the decline and insisted that Tokyo is not 
abiding by the bilateral trade agreement. It is viewed by the 
United States as a commitment but as a nonbinding target by 
Japan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

