<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry To Improve Image of Diplomats </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0603070894 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 6 Mar 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0603070894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 6 Mar 94 Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] The Ministry of Foreign Affairs plans to play its 
part in portraying a better image of Japan. Beginning this 
spring, the ministry plans to begin improving the look of 
Japanese ambassadors and other diplomats by having them listen 
to advice from experts so they can present their best 
impressions when appearing in television interviews. As stated 
by a Foreign Ministry source, it is felt "there are not many 
diplomats who are used to the mass media." Therefore, the 
ministry plans to launch a campaign to promote diplomacy in a 
manner "which makes Japan visible" by making on-the-job 
improvements in its diplomatic stance, a stance which has often 
been described abroad as being "hard to understand." 
  Those who are to newly undergo this "media training" program 
are mostly diplomats who have the greatest chance of being 
interviewed by the mass media, such as ambassadors and directors 
of overseas centers for public relations and cultural affairs. 
Japanese diplomatic missions overseas will sign contracts with 
consultants who will review video recordings of the interviews 
of various diplomats and check on minute details--such as their 
pronunciation, accents, pauses in speech, gestures, and even 
their tastes in neckties. In this way, the consultants will 
determine how the diplomats can most effectively appeal to their 
audiences in future interviews with the mass media. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

