<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Keidanren, Rengo Agree on Administrative Reform </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1103055494 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 8 Mar 94 
Evening Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1103055494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Top officials of Keidanren [Federation of Economic 
Organizations of Japan] and Rengo [Japanese Trade Union 
Confederation] held a meeting at a Tokyo hotel on 8 March to 
discuss establishing a third-party organization aimed at 
promoting administrative reform, and deregulation in particular. 
They agreed that the third-party organization should be managed 
by the private sector without members who are ex-governmental 
officials. Japan-U.S. relations have become stressed due to 
Japan's surplus. Both Keidanren and Rengo believe that Japan 
should aim at reducing the surplus by promoting structural 
reform, particularly through deregulation, and that deregulation 
conducted mainly by bureaucrats may be limited in its effect. 
Keidanren Chairman Gaishi Hiraiwa and other top officials 
intend to make a formal proposal on their demands to top 
officials of the Management and Coordination Agency [MCA], 
including Director General Koshiro Ishida on 24 March. 
  The concept of setting up a third-party body is based on the 
recommendations previously made by the "Economic Reform Study 
Council" (known as the Hiraiwa Council) and the Ad Hoc Council 
for Promoting Administrative Reform. The MCA is currently 
studying details of this body. However, Keidanren thinks "the 
fact that bureaucrats, mainly from the MCA, assume leadership in 
working out the bill is, in itself, a problem," (according to 
the Keidanren Secretariat). Thus, top Keidanren and Rengo 
officials decided to discuss this matter in depth. 
  During the meeting, Rengo Secretary General Washio said: "As 
a third-party organization, it should exclude members who speak 
for the government ministries and agencies and it should select 
members mainly from the private sector. It should have an 
independent secretariat and be granted rights to recommend 
investigations and to order submission of related documents." 
  Keidanren Vice Chairman Isao Nakauchi said: "I quite agree 
with you." Thus, the participants agreed on excluding former 
governmental officials. 
  With regard to the issue of reducing Japan's surplus, they 
agreed that "while we oppose setting up numerical targets, it is 
necessary to promote cutting the surplus in various ways, 
including expansion of domestic demand." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-5856 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas048__a94019" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-048-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 March 1994 </DATE1>

