<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official To Visit U.S. on Talks Resumption </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1203055594 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 12 
Mar 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1203055594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 12 March Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] The Ministry of Foreign Affairs [MOFA] on 11 March 
revealed that Sadayuki Hayashi, who was named deputy 
vice-minister of foreign affairs the same day, would visit the 
United States next week and meet with Bowman Cutter, deputy 
assistant to the President (for economic policy) who is the U.S. 
official in charge of the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks. 
The purpose is to look for clues on reopening the framework 
talks. 
  The United States says it will "decide on reopening the 
talks 
after studying the substance of the market liberalization 
measures to be finalized by the Japanese Government by the end 
of March," (according to Secretary of State Christopher), but 
there are unclear points, such as which area of measures the 
United States is most interested in. The MOFA is hoping to find 
out the accurate intentions of the U.S. Government and use this 
information in helping restore the relations between the 
countries. 
  In meetings with Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and 
Foreign 
Minister Tsutomu Hata, Secretary Christopher urged Japan to come 
up with import promotion measures which will be effective, 
saying, "Ambiguous steps are not good." Regarding market 
liberalization plans, the Japanese Government has offered to 
finalize them in two steps -- doing part of them by the end of 
March, and the rest of them by the end of June. Christopher's 
remark is believed to have been a warning to Japan against using 
this "two-step formula" as an excuse for delays, and for not 
coming up with any effective measures in March. 
  Resuming and making progress in the framework talks can be a 
justification for stopping the imposition of the Super 301 
provision (definition of unfair trade practices and nations 
engaged in such practices, and sanctions against them). Thus, 
MOFA wants to put emphasis on the work of finding out the true 
intentions of the United States with respect to resumption of 
the talks. 

</TEXT>

