<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Steps To Open Markets to U.S. Products Studied </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1203135194 Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN in Japanese 11 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1203135194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The government is currently racking its brains for 
devising measures to open Japan's markets to U.S. products. On 
10 March, it decided to review Japanese business practices and 
the keiretsu system of interlocking corporate groups -- which 
have drawn severe criticism from foreign countries -- looking 
for possible measures to reduce Japan's trade surplus. 
  A "distribution and market opening division" is to be 
established under the Administrative Reform Promotion 
Headquarters to discuss deregulatory measures which can produce 
immediate effects. The government plans to ask the division to 
discuss business practices and review them. This idea has 
already been approved by Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and 
has been conveyed to each ministry as the prime minister's plan. 
  According to a government source, the government decided to 
review business practices because: 1) the United States has not 
been satisfied with the measures that Japan has worked out to 
cut its trade surplus, and the government has faced difficulties 
formulating measures to open markets in priority trade areas, 
such as autos and auto parts, which resulted in the breakup of 
the Japan-U.S. framework trade talks; and 2) Japanese business 
practices lie behind arguments that "Japan is different from 
other countries" and behind U.S. demands for Japan to set 
numerical targets, as well as its impatient actions toward 
imposing sanctions on Japan. 
  The government is worried that the United States and other 
countries might intensify their criticism that "Japan's trade 
surplus is aggravating the world's employment situation" through 
a G-7 job summit scheduled in Detroit this month and a Naples 
summit in July. 
  The distribution and market opening division, which will be 
inaugurated at the end of March, is to review business practices 
and the keiretsu system. Specifically, it will review keiretsu 
transactions among interconnected business groups and groups in 
which banks form the central elements. Also, it will discuss 
group boycotting, a practice in which a group of companies 
prevent newcomers from entering their markets, as well as 
collusive bidding practices in tenders for public works 
projects. The division is expected to reach a conclusion before 
the Naples summit. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

