<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Coalition, Ruling Parties Question TMD Use </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1303043394 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 12 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1303043394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In a 11 March Japan-U.S. Committee for 
Consultations on Security meeting, Defense Agency Director 
General Kazuo Aichi expressed his desire to somehow adopt the 
concept of the Theater Missile Defense [TMD] system in the new 
defense program, which will replace the existing "defense 
program outline." However, now views in the government and 
coalition parties are emerging questioning his TMD position, 
citing the (1969) Diet resolution on peaceful use of space and 
the doubtful performance of interceptor missiles. It is 
apparent that the matter will have to undergo further 
adjustments of views. 
  In the meeting, Director General Aichi said: "As far as I am 
concerned, I would like to present a concept (on TMD) in the 
revised program for defense." 
  Even if this concept comes to be adopted, the expression for 
"TMD" is expected to be changed to something like "missile 
defense improvement" in the new defense program. It is likely 
that the United States has taken "the remark (of Aichi) as 
Japan's pledge for cooperation in the TMD program." 
  Within the ruling coalition parties, the Social Democratic 
Party of Japan [SDPJ] thinks the TMD concept goes against the 
Diet resolution on the peaceful use of space. On the other 
hand, from other parties there are strong voices asking: "Can 
the system cope with the Nodong-1 missiles of the DPRK (North 
Korea)?" because of the recent reports that data show the 
Patriot missiles that came into the limelight in the Gulf war in 
fact had poor accuracy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

