<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Okinawa Governor on Bilateral Security Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1303060394 Naha RYUKYU SHIMPO in Japanese 13 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1303060394 </F>
<F P=104>  Naha RYUKYU SHIMPO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On 11 March, Okinawa Governor Masahide Ota, 
commenting on the Japan-U.S. Security Consultative Committee's 
taking up issues regarding the streamlining and consolidation of 
U.S. military bases on Okinawa, including the early return of 
Yomitan Auxiliary Airfield, said: "This was a big step forward 
in resolving military base issues. It is hoped that concrete 
steps will be taken to bring about the consolidation and 
retrenchment of U.S. military forces and facilities." 
  The governor thanked Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata and 
Defense Agency Director General Kazuo Aichi, saying: "The fact 
that issues concerning the consolidation and retrenchment of 
U.S. military facilities in Okinawa were taken up at the highest 
level of consultations between Japan and the United States 
regarding security and other relevant affairs indicates a big 
step has been taken in resolving problems related to military 
bases, such as the return of U.S. military bases and prevention 
of damage caused by military bases." 
  Governor Ota also expressed some expectations, adding: "As 
indicated in such developments as the recent visit to the United 
States by Ichiro Yoneyama, director general of the Defense 
Facilities Administration Agency, the Japanese and U.S. 
Governments have come to understand the importance of military 
base issues and have thus decided to come to the negotiating 
table. It is very encouraging since this indicates that 
prospects are growing brighter toward bringing about a solution 
to our problems." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

