<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Outcome of Security Consultative Talks Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1503040994 Naha OKINAWA TIMES in Japanese 13 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 5 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1503040994 </F>
<F P=104>  Naha OKINAWA TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "Persistent Anti-Military-Base Move Is Needed"] </F>
  [Text] A Japan-U.S. foreign and defense ministerial 
Security Consultative Committee meeting was held at the prime 
minister's official residence in Tokyo on 11 March. At the 
meeting, the issue of U.S. military bases on Okinawa was taken 
up. In a joint announcement released after the meeting, it was 
specified that "the two sides pledged to continue their efforts 
for consolidation and realignment of facilities and areas, 
particularly on Okinawa." 
  At a vice ministerial meeting held at the Defense Agency 
after the joint announcement was released, U.S. Defense 
Undersecretary Frank Wisner reportedly hinted at the possibility 
of the early return of the Yomitan Auxiliary Airfield. 
  Since the coalition government was inaugurated, Okinawa 
Prefectural Governor Ota; concerned cities, towns, and villages; 
and civic groups have been looking forward to seeing progress in 
talks on military base affairs. We appreciate the fact that at 
the first security consultative committee meeting under the new 
government, the United States indicated a forward-looking 
attitude on the return of lands being used by the U.S. forces 
and the abolition of military practices. 
  When the U.S. official's remarks on the return of the 
Yomitan 
Auxiliary Airfield by end of this year were reported, Yomitan 
residents welcomed the report with happy expectations. However, 
the relocation of the parachute training area and the 
maintenance of functions of the adjacent communications facility 
are preconditions for materializing the "early return" of the 
Yomitan Auxiliary Airfield. When Director General Yoneyama of 
the Defense Facilities Administration Agency [DFAA] visited the 
United States on 26 February, a high-raking U.S. official showed 
him a forward-looking attitude in connection with the return of 
the airfield. In view of this, it can be said that Defense 
Undersecretary Wisner's reported remarks were to reconfirm what 
the high-ranking U.S. official said to DFAA Director-General 
Yoneyama. 
  About this time last year, it was constantly reported that 
the U.S. forces were considering relocating the parachute 
training area to Camp Hansen adjacent to Kin town and Ginoza 
village, which later objected to the relocation of the training 
area. Unless this issue involving both Kin town and Ginoza 
village is settled, Yomitan villagers will not be able to openly 
welcome the return of the Yomitan Auxiliary Airfield. 
  At the ministerial meeting, Foreign Minister Hata and 
Defense 
Agency Director General Aichi singled out the issues stemming 
from the military bases and called for the return of the Naha 
Port, the stoppage of live-fire exercise across highway 104, and 
the return of the Yomitan Auxiliary Airfield. In response, 
Secretary of State Christopher reportedly said that he is aware 
of the situation. 
  If the U.S. forces should again study possible construction 
of the parachuting training area in Kin town, which is calling 
for stopping the live-fire exercise, it would run counter to the 
Japan-U.S. announcement that "the two sides pledged to continue 
their efforts for consolidation and realignment of facilities 
and areas." 
  The two governments have to bring those issues to a 
satisfactory settlement with the outcome of the ministerial 
meeting confirming that each military base issue is an important 
issue to be solved. 
  The Japan-U.S. Security Consultative Committee, which was 
originally started as a vice ministerial-level meeting, was 
upgraded to a ministerial meeting in December 1990. The two 
sides held the first ministerial meeting recently with the goal 
of reconfirming the two countries' stand of maintaining the 
Japan-U.S. security system amid worsening bilateral economic and 
trade relations. 
  On the issue of military bases on Okinawa, the joint 
announcement says: "The continued harmonious use of facilities 
and areas by U.S. forces in Japan is indispensable to deterrence 
and to the readiness of U.S. forces in Japan." We believe that 
maintaining harmonious relations between towns and villages is 
also indispensable in addition to harmonious relations between 
the locals and U.S. forces. 
  The Yomitan Village Office has already mapped out its own 
plan for use of lands after their return. But before that, it 
is necessary to solve such issues as land ownership involving 
former land owners and farmers who are tacitly allowed to engage 
in farming in the area of the Yomitan Auxiliary Airfield. At 
the same time, it is necessary to take this opportunity to give 
impetus to moves calling for the return of military bases and 
the solution of issues resulting from military exercises. 

</TEXT>

