<H3> <TI>   ROK-Japanese Shipbuilding Circles Hold Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1403085994 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 13 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 9 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1403085994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Top officials of the Japanese and ROK shipbuilding 
circles held a meeting in a Tokyo hotel on the afternoon of 12 
March. While Japan, which is suffering from sluggish prices of 
ships, called on the ROK to curb the buildup of its facilities, 
the ROK refused by saying, "Japan's demand is against the move 
toward liberalization." Thus, they failed to reach an accord. 
  Another meeting of shipbuilders of Japan, the ROK, and 
European countries is scheduled for 14 and 15 March. 
  Several ROK builders, including the Samsung Heavy Industrial 
Company, have so far announced plans to build new docks for very 
large crude carriers (VLCC). With regard to their plans, 
Japanese representatives led by Shigeru Aida, chairman of the 
Shipbuilders Association of Japan, (chairman of Sumitomo Heavy 
Industries Ltd.), urged self-restraint on the buildup of 
facilities, insisting: "There is already a surplus in 
shipbuilding facilities in the world. Building more facilities 
will cause excessive competition for contracts." 
  However, ROK Shipbuilders Association Chairman Song Yong-su, 
(president of the Hanchin Heavy Industrial Company), and other 
participants insisted on difficulties in curbing the buildup of 
facilities, explaining: "We would like Japan to understand our 
circumstances. After the change of political regime, everything 
is moving toward liberalization." 
  Thanks to the increase in the yen's value against the won, 
the number of orders received by the ROK has been increasing in 
recent years, becoming number one in the world in 1993, 
exceeding that of Japan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

